CLINICAL HISTORY:  Epilepsy, currently seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS:   Lamictal, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 38-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy, current seizure­
free.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Digital video EEG is performed using standard
10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation. This is an awake through stage II sleep record in an individual who is very drowsy.
In maximum wakefulness there is an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm. Vertex waves are noted in sleep, as are post.
Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background slowing. The patient is falling asleep in photic stimulation.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits but excessively drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are noted. The excessive drowsiness can be due to sleep deprivations, medications or a warm environment.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with episodes of bilateral hand shaking and
loss of awareness. These episodes stopped after the patient began Depakote therapy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were preformed. This was a 1 hour sleep-deprived study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing and anterior
spread of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background
slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this
EEG nor in the previous EEG. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old male with recurrent vertigo and fatigue.
MEDICATIONS: Os-Cal, Nexium, Lexapro, Albuterol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with 9.5 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized
by slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles are observed
in stage 2 sleep. Photic stimulation is performed after the patient has been asleep.
There is a driving response observed, though the patient is drifting in an out of sleep.
Hyperventilation produces a scant amount of background slowing.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed in this EEG. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important
consideration, a repeat study capturing one of his spells is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:    38 year old right handed woman with migraine headaches, depression and a sharp pain in her head.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Seroquel, Zolpidem, Nabumetone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG is well-organized. There is a relatively fast alpha rhythm of 12 Hz with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation produces an increased in amplitude of the background. This is followed by a drowsy and then stage I sleep with vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed concurrently and do not active the record. In fact, the patient seems to drift into stage II sleep at the close of this study.
HR: 	66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low voltage, but there is
an 8.5 hertz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of background beta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing in the background. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by an increase in theta. Hypersynchronous activity is noted in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

CLINICAL CORR  ELATION: There are no epileptiform features observed. If further characterization of her epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing sleep is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed male with head trauma in 1982, now losing track of time, depression,  anxiety, forgetfulness. Episodes of forgetfulness increasing in stress but none for the last month.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Glyburide, Actoplus, Aceon
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized with 10 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Occasional temporal wicket is observed. The patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background followed by drowsiness.  More extensive stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are observed later on in the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at faster flash frequencies.
HR:	78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The wicket activity described above is a normal variant.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	39 year old right handed male with daily headaches, evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine,  Zolpidem, Elavil, Cymbalta, Norvasc, Gabapentin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and primarily asleep EEG with photic stimulation but without hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and posts.   The patient is awakened for photic stimulation and has limited wakefulness.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  The primarily sleep EEG could be due to sleep deprivation or other disturbances like hypersomnolence, or even a sleep-deprived EEG. There are no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with a feeling of disequilibrium
and presyncope, admitted in July 2009.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10
Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an
increase in background slowing. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes,
spindles and POSTS. The patient is quite sleepy and transitions in and out of stage II
sleep. The POSTS are of slightly higher amplitude on the left. Hyperventilation
produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The
amplitude asymmetry of the POSTS is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old woman with multiple events in the clinic today admitted with episode of unresponsiveness  and mutism.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.  The patient is awake and cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well defined 9.3 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage fronto-central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by the appearance of rhythmic theta.
HR: 	90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Of note, this record was
recorded immediately after this patient's multiple and prolonged events. Hence, not only were the behaviors unusual for seizures, but there was no postictal slowing.

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake record.

After photic stimulation is over, the patient had some jerking of her shoulders but not in association with the flashing lights. After the photic stimulation continues, the recording continues and the patient had intermittent jerking of her shoulders. The shoulders jerk forwards and backwards.

The shoulder jerking is not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG. It is sometimes associated with upwards thrusting of her upper chest. She stares straight ahead during the events.

As the record continues, a physician examines the patient. The interaction with the physician and the patient is associated with increasing motor activity including eye blinking, mouth opening and closing, a little bit of alternating movements to right or left, and then some rotatory movements of the torso. When the movements stop, the EEG shows a normal awake pattern. The patient is staring off to space after the event ends.

The event begins at 9:58 and lasts 7 minutes. Afterwards, there is intermittent jerking. Cognitive testing is not performed to make certain that the patient is responsive at the end of the EEG.

HR: 60 bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a 7-minute behavioral episode without EEG change. This recording suggests a behavioral event rather than an electrical seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed male with epilepsy, hepatitis C and liver
disease admitted after multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were
performed. The patient had one of his spells during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm with
occasional background theta particularly in the temporal regions. Hyperventilation is performed
early-on in the record producing an increase in generalized slowing. This is follow by
drowsiness with increased rhythmic slowing followed by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles
and then arousals.
At 11:59, the patient is awake. He shifts about. He is awake during photic stimulation which
elicits a brief driving response.
The patient has a spell during the EEG. This is at 12:10. at 12:10:56, he is moving about. He is
unresponsive with a technician. During the section at 12:10:52, the patient has right facial
twitching and he has some movements of his left arm. He does not answer questions to the
technologist. The patient is not entirely on camera. The EEG demonstrates an awake pattern
with an artifact at C3T3. He is amnestic for the event. Unfortunately during this spell the
technician is trying to repair the C3 electrode. He is described as having alternating right facial
or left hand movements. There is no definitive EEG signature for these behaviors.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits but with unusual behavior.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the electrode problems, there was no EEG scalp
signature for this patient's behavior.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed gentleman with a long history of depression, epilepsy, cerebral palsy, subsequent aneurysm repair. Last seizure 05/11/2011 with loss of consciousness and confusion.

craniotomy. Overall, most of the focal slowing in this record is centrotemporal. In the context of a breech rhythm, there are a handful of right central or frontal sharp waves. Photic stimulation is  performed while the patient is in stage 2 sleep. No significant driving response was noted.

IMPRESSION: A normal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic theta and delta activity in the right temporal region.
2. Rare G4 and F4 sharp waves identified in the context of a breech rhythm.

in the right for this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old right handed female with a history of refractory epilepsy, seizure free until she was switched to generic Tegretol.  Neuronal migrational disorder and psychiatric history.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old right handed woman with generalized anxiety disorder, constant seizures, depression, and heart murmur.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.   Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz 40 mV alpha rhythm.  There is generous frontal central beta. IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness to stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The prominent beta may be due to medications for anxiety or other causes. This EEG was compared to a previous EEG in 2009, this is her second, normal, EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old right handed woman with asthma, depression, 3 strokes, positional dizziness, and frequent headaches. Syncope.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed female with seizures since age 14, presents with refractory episodes, here for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Hyperventilation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an increased amount of beta activity seen diffusely throughout the EEG.  During the recording, the patient is recorded only during wakefulness.  The only activating procedure that is performed is hyperventilation, during which she has an episode which I will describe below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
Events:  During this recording, while the patient was doing hyperventilation she suddenly stopped responding, started moving her throat and jerking her back and forth repeatedly.  At times she would move to the left and then to the right.  During this episode, the tech stimulated her feet and she would respond and at times appeared to follow commands, but would not verbalize.  The whole episode of unresponsiveness lasted some minutes, but with the clinical presentation lasted about 12 minutes.  During this recording, the EEG revealed prominent muscle artifact but a nice posterior dominant rhythm could be seen at times and normal EEG could be seen at times throughout the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG with an episode of unresponsiveness as described above with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a nonepileptic event, likely psychogenic in nature.  Otherwise this is a normal awake EEG and no seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  25 year old right handed male with epilepsy in childhood, seizure free until 3 years ago when he had a seizure and then another one as if he was falling off to sleep.  His girlfriend noticed shaking and he awoke with a headache.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 37 year old man with pneumonia, obstructive sleep apnea, COPD, hypertension presented with extreme shortness of breath for 2 days, lower extremity edema with episode of dizziness for 1 month.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient also has some normal frontal central beta while awake, however, the patient easily drowses up and goes into sleep and quickly goes into stage I, stage II sleep.  The majority of the recording is in sleep as the patient easily falls asleep.  No activating procedures were performed.

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG with limited wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.   Please note that the shortened sleep latency may represent sleep architecture abnormality and further evaluation with a sleep consultation study may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed woman with new onset of seizures who was unconsciousness, unable to speak, and left face twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, patient events, and alarms, as well as nurses events were noted to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  In the middle of the night some electrodes became dislodged and there is some electrode artifact by the end of the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep and normal stages I to III with sleep are recorded.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Episodes:  The patient had 3 episodes throughout the recording.  The first one occurred at 12:34 p.m. at the onset of the recording where she started having left facial twitching, followed by unresponsiveness while continuing to have left facial twitching.  This event lasted for about 2 minutes and then the patient became reactive again.
The second event occurred at 8:18 p.m.  The patient suddenly started having left facial twitching and grimacing, as well as tightening her arms, as well as becoming unresponsive.  This was followed by staring and mouth movements.  The episode lasted for over 4 minutes.
At about 3:32 a.m. the patient suddenly started having diffuse body shaking and rocking, as well as facial twitching.  This was much more severe than the other ones.  She continued rocking, jerking, and being unresponsive.  Then after stopping the jerking she laid in bed and remained unresponsive and started moving her mouth rhythmically in a chewing fashion.  The whole event lasted for about 4.5 minutes.
The EEG during the whole 3 events revealed a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform correlate to any of the events.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG and 3 non-epileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  Note:  The 3 events described above did not have an EEG correlate which is consistent with a diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39 year old right handed male with history of right ankle pain and narcotic abuse, now with episodes of loss of consciousness with diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside for 4.5 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, as well as patient alarm events, and nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm with normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Events:  The patient had about 9 events which consisted of him pressing the alarm, suddenly his arms would become flexed, and he would become stiff and grimacing his face, lasting for about 20-30 seconds, during the episode and after which he would be unresponsive for another 2-3 minutes.  The behavior was very similar to the ones that he described before and every episode remained the same.  During these episodes the EEG would have a diffuse muscle artifact, but underlying it there would be a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform discharges prior to the flexing, posturing, or after when he would remain unresponsive.  It looked like a normal EEG.  Sometimes with the flexor posturing he would hip thrust during the event.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with events with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The events that were captured and described as above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed gentleman with diabetes and hypertension, syncopal event March 3, after taking tramadol, felt lightheaded.  Past history of a prior event which was similar.  In this most recent event, he was unconscious for 5 minutes and was confused afterwards.
MEDICATIONS:  No seizure medications.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz 30 mV posterior dominant rhythm.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is occasional, isolated right or left temporal mixed theta-delta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in rhythmic theta.
Vertex waves and POSTs are identified in sleep which is not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The occasional right or left temporal slowing in drowsiness is a nonspecific finding, but can be seen in
those with atherosclerotic disease risk factors.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study with more prolonged sleep can be obtained.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal single lead EEG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTY:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation produced no abnormal discharges, however, see below for photic stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  During photic stimulation, the patient started having slow movements of her head side to side then started twitching her upper extremities and moving her body towards the right side and appeared to be unresponsive to commands.  This episode lasted for a period of about 40 seconds and then she remained with her eyes closed and appeared to be slightly more responsive.  Minutes later, photic stimulation was performed again after she had opened her eyes and appeared to have followed commands.  At that point she started jerking her left shoulder slowly, then trembling her upper extremities and again falling towards the right side of the seat.  This second episode lasted for about approximately a minute and 20 seconds.  During both episodes, the EEG revealed a normal awake background with no epileptiform abnormalities and no EEG correlate to this behavior described above.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG with two episodes of shaking during photic stimulation with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG with no seizures or epileptiform discharges.  The episodes captured above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with nonepileptic events.  No seizure.

LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/19/2012 to 06/20/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient recalls 3 episodes.  The first is on the 19th at noon where she felt a little startled.  The second was at 10 p.m. where she felt a mini aura characterized by tingling sensation on her face.  She did not recall an episode at 5:25, although she did push the button for a tingling sensation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity.
Event time 11:22:  There is a burst of rhythmic left temporal theta delta with frequency evolution.  This is 5 seconds in duration.  There is no push button at that time.
Event time 5:25:20 p.m.:   A burst of rhythmic theta, frequency was subtle, frequency evolution lasting only 3 seconds.  Thirty seconds later the patient reports the mini-aura which she no longer recalled.
Event time 9:58 p.m.  No abnormalities on the EEG were identified at that time.
Event time10:25 a.m.:  There was another burst lasting 4 seconds in duration in the morning on the 20th which is similar to the 2 prior bursts.   No clinical features were recalled.
HR:    60 bpm
INTERVAL IMPRESSION:  There are 3 bursts of rhythmic theta from the left temporal region with frequency evolution.  These are concerning as a potential interictal epileptiform discharge.  They may also be clinically significant with the mini-auras that the patient experienced.
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12- 72 – 06/20/2012 TO 06/21/2012
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a well defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is a sleep deprived record.  Around 10:00 p.m. the patient seems to be trying to stay up.  The EEG demonstrates small EPOCHS where the patient seems to be drowsy.   Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles. The data is reviewed for the clinical symptoms that the patient experienced, but no epileptiform features are identified.
HR:    66 bpm
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/21/2012 TO 06/22/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient reported an aura at 8 p.m. on the 21st.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Around 8 p.m., the patient is noted to transition in and out of stage 2 sleep, waking up and falling back asleep.  Fragments of deeper stages of sleep are noted overnight.
No electrographic seizures were identified.  The seizure and spike detector did not identify any other epileptiform abnormalities.
Event time 11:55:  The patient pushes the button at 11:56:12 stating that she feels as if she is about to have an aura.  She puts her hand to her chest and later appears to be tearful.  The EEG is awake at this time.  No epileptiform features were noted.   For her 8:00 p.m. the patient reported symptoms that her throat was closing with the seizure.

HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
3 bursts of rhythmic, paroxysmal theta, all less than 4 seconds in duration, but with frequency evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's clinical symptoms did not appear to be associated with well-defined epileptiform abnormalities.  On one day, however, there were discharges which appear epileptiform in nature.  While this patient did not have any of her larger spells with head turning, a feeling as if her throat was closing or impairment of awareness, this record does not exclude a diagnosis and clinically, diagnosis may be considered.

MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra
REASON FOR  STUDY:  Seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient's EEG was reviewed using continuous spike and seizure detection software, in addition to the patient's learned event as well as nurses' notes.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a mild excessive amount of beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I, stage II, and stage III sleep, as well as stage IV.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   None
SEIZURE/EVENT:  During the recording, the patient presses the alarm around 7:39 p.m. and describes that she feels like she is going to have an event.  There are no EEG changes at that time.  At 09:24:51, the patient presses the alarm and starts shaking her body, arching her back, and stretching her legs.  She lifts up the sheets at times and cannot be seen in the video.  She continues to do this for about 7 to 8 minutes until nurses come in and she is unresponsive to questions.  She remains having irregular jerking movements.  During this entire time, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The episode captured during this EEG had no EEG correlate, which is consistent with a nonepileptic psychogenic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  31 year old right handed gentleman with 1-year history of epilepsy.  The patient was a steel worker who fell 20-30 feet 2 years ago.  Suffered a loss of consciousness. MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  The drowsy pattern is relatively symmetric and on rare occasions, the slow activity seems to be slightly slower on the right compared to the left.  This is more apparent with the use of frequency analysis.  Hyperventilation produces bilateral theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous, bilateral driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.  There is vigorous harmonic driving and supraharmonic driving identified from both hemispheres.  The driving response is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right, but the overall frequency differences are relatively symmetric.  On some occasions, the supraharmonic driving seems to be bit a more prominent on the right.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:   EEG is at the limit of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Simple visual analysis of the EEG would not otherwise identify the subtle asymmetries described above.  In this individual with head trauma, the subtle features on the right may be evaluated by imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed man, with a history of seizures with Xanax withdrawal, anxiety, and hypertension, presents for episodes of strange things in mouth with quick recall of events.  He is here for classification of epileptic versus non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode. DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage 1, stage 2, and deep stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENT:  During the recording the patient had 5 events where he would suddenly start shaking his head from side to side.  Sometimes towards the left and sometimes toward the right irregularly while becoming unresponsive and remaining so for minutes at time, sometimes for more than 5-10 minutes, and intermittently starting and stopping the behavior.  These  episodes, the first one which occurred at 3:28 p.m., the second one occurred at 9:23 p.m., the third one occurred around 2:40 a.m., and another one at 7:51 a.m., and the last one at 8:48 am had no EEG correlate other than a muscle artifact and afterwards there was normal posterior dominant rhythm seen, all consistent with nonepileptic events.

IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episodes captured above with head shaking had no EEG correlate.  As such, they are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic events. Please note that this patient had previous records which showed left temporal sharp waves.  This was not seen during this admission.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  18 year old right handed female syncopal spell lasting 25 seconds.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and a sleep record in very drowsy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, exceeding 70 mV with posterior slow waves of youth.  In drowsiness there is hypersynchronous rhythmic higher amplitude theta frequency activity “hypnogogic”, “hypersynchrony”.  There were 1 or 2 points of head rocking artifact and there were 1-2 bursts which are slightly asynchronous. Hyperventilation produces hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude, somewhat sharply contoured theta frequency activity, but no definitive spike and wave activity. The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Other features of drowsiness include the hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG demonstrates multiple normal variants for a young adult.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There was no definitive spike and wave activity, although hyperventilation did produce some rhythmic high amplitude theta.  There were a handful of slightly asynchronous bursts as the patient transitions to drowsiness.  If absence seizures are an important consideration, a repeat fasting EEG, perhaps with a second hyperventilation session maybe helpful.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient's impedances were inappropriate, specifically in the occipital electrodes which caused some multi-electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that appears to reach 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient had some normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures did not produce any abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I/stage II.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
One single sharp transient maximal at F3 seen in the recording while drowsy.
Occasional small amplitude sharp spikes seen at T3, only in stage I sleep, although not seen over T2.  The morphology is most consistent with benign epileptiform transients of sleep (BETS).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal limited EEG with one suspicious left frontal sharp transient and BETS.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The significance of the left frontal sharp transient is unclear.  A repeated recording should be performed.  Particularly in this patient where the impedances and the quality of the recording was poor, it should be repeated free of charge.  The BETS are benign and do not indicate a high correlation with an epileptogenic focus in that region.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old right handed woman with seizures since age 16, now refractory to medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Valproic Acid, Lovenox, Depakote, Keppra, Klonopin, Zoloft, Haldol, Terazosin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software as well as nurses' notes and patient's alarms were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage 1, stage 2 and deeper stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  The patient had 2 events in this recording similar to the ones in the previous day.  The first one occurred at 8:10:43 p.m. and the second one occurred at 11:47 p.m.  Both of them, the body had irregular shaking for minutes with no response to verbal or motor commands.  The patient had no EEG correlate during this time despite being unconscious.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with 2 episodes of nonepileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The 2 episodes described above had no EEG correlate, as such it is consistent with nonepileptic seizures.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 49-year-old gentleman who had a seizure yesterday in the setting of severe tachycardia and desaturation to a pulse ox of 35.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan given yesterday, citalopram.
INTRODUCTION:
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient is asleep throughout the majority of the EEG.  During very brief wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 8.5 Hz with anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Throughout the majority of the study, the patient is asleep with vertex waves, sleep spindles, and POSTS seen.  Also, REM sleep is observed by the end of the recording.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  No epileptiform discharges were observed.
FINDINGS:  Primarily asleep study to REM sleep at the end of the recording.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal primarily asleep and briefly awake EEG due to excessive drowsiness and REM sleep captured on a 22-minute study.  These findings indicate excessive drowsiness.  In a routine EEG, a finding of REM sleep is abnormal.  In a proper clinical setting, further investigation to causes of excessive sleepiness may be considered.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not exclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with epilepsy since age 12.  Subsequent cocaine dependence.  After a seizure, patient became violent.  Seizures characterized by an aura of strange feeling followed by postictal confusion.  Last seizure 1 day ago. The patient asked the technologist if photic stimulation would produce 1 of his typical seizures.  The technologist told him that, that was a possibility.  The patient subsequently had 1 of typical behaviors during photic stimulation, but after the photic stimulation had stopped.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a scant amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the EEG and produces and increase an amplitude of the background.  Vertex waves and POSTS are observed in stage 1 sleep with brief stage 2 sleep.  The patient was falling asleep during photic stimulation and transitioning in and out of sleep during photic stimulation.
The patient had an event during photic stimulation.  The patient was drowsy prior to photic stimulations, the patient was waking up, although there were brief transitions in and out of sleep.
The patient was awake at the end of the 11 Hz stimuli, when the behavior occurred, he sat up abruptly.  His eyes were dilated, he was moving back and forth and his heart rate increased briefly to 150 BPM.
Although the audio was not working, the patient was able to communicate during the event.
There were no epileptiform features noted during the event.  No postictal features were identified.
Heart rate 78-150 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  The EEG is normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient had an unusual behavior.  The patient was clearly awake for several seconds prior to the event, but he had been drifting in and out of sleep.  The event had no epileptiform features, but a link either to a sleep-related disorder or a psychiatric illness may be considered.

As the patient becomes drowsy, theta is identified from the temporal regions bilaterally.
Mu activity was noted, but testing was not performed to confirm this.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was drifting off to sleep, but did elicit a driving response.  Photic stimulation elicited harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this individual.  The first EEG immediately after his symptoms was associated with left temporal focal slowing, but this EEG is normal.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy since 18 months of age. The patient reports grand mal, petite mal and complex partial seizures.  The seizures occur during sleep, the last seizure was 10 days ago.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz 40 microvolt alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Prominent mu activity is noted with 8 Hz activity in the central regions particularly on the left although testing was not performed to confirm this.  Mu rhythm was also noted in the right central region as the recording continued.  Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  The overall EEG is relatively high voltage with a very prominent mu activity.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness produces an increase in beta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.  In some sections of the record there is a question of an alpha sub-harmonic.
Heart rate 72 b.p.m.
IMPRESSION:  This is an interesting but normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient has an interesting but normal EEG including the mu activity and the alpha rhythm with the alpha supra-harmonic.  No epileptiform features were identified.  If additional information is needed to characterize this individual's epilepsy, a more prolonged study can be considered.  Although benzodiazepines were not listed in this patient's medications, benzodiazepines or other similar medications might account for the prominent beta noted in the record.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old woman with history of seizures since childhood, now transferred from Episcopal because of a seizure during a stress test and now having recurrent seizures of unresponsiveness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection, as well as seizure detection software, nurses events, patient's alarm events were all used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient has normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Patient events:  The patient had an event at 7:26 in the morning.  She pressed the alarm, laid in bed, and became unresponsive to any verbal or motor commands.  She continued to be unresponsive for about 3 minutes, after which the doctor came in and tested her.  She started crying and appeared to be slow to answer commands, but finally ended up answering commands.  She continued crying during this event.  During the entire event there was no abnormal EEG findings and remained as a normal awake EEG.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The patient's event in which she was unresponsive had no EEG correlate.  As such, it is consistent with the diagnosis of nonepileptic psychogenic event.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Portable EEG.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old male with a history of seizures and hypertension presents with seizure-like activities described as acting weird, staring, confusion, and EMS noted generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include phenobarbital and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1-channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through a stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency and 30-35 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is presence of low amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background activity and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of the vertex sharp waves.  Stage II sleep was captured characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles. Heart rate was 90-100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic metabolic hypoxic or infectious encephalopathy, alternatively it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including phenobarbital or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform discharges abnormalities or seizures were captured during this record.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.  The absence of epileptiform activities or seizures does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 47-year-old man with episodes of dizziness followed by loss of consciousness and decreased responsiveness.  His last episode was several days ago.

There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  No sleep was captured. There is nearly continuous T3 electrode artifact throughout the recording.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
Nearly continuous T3 electrode artifact.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake only, 22 minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persistent, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.

Very brief drowsiness was characterized by a decrease in muscle artifact, attenuation of the alpha rhythm, and an increase in theta.  Rare lambda was noted in wakefulness with rare POSTS noted in sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  96 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The general theta described above may be related to this patient's benzodiazepine use.  If additional information is needed, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old male with a history of head trauma, adult-onset epilepsy, and likely nonepileptic seizures as well.  The patient typically has seizures after encounters with the health care system and has many adverse reactions to antiepileptic drugs.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was a very drowsy patient.

Vertex waves were noted in stage 1 sleep.  As the patient drifted off to sleep, there was an involuntary jerk of the right leg. This was not associated with epileptiform features.  Cognitive testing was performed at the end to make sure that the patient was maximally awake and there was an awake pattern and then the patient quickly started to become a little drowsy with slowing of the alpha rhythm.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform activity was noted.  Sleep myoclonus was noted on one occasion which does not carry an EEG correlate.  This patient appears to be excessively drowsy which could be related to sleep deprivation or the use of opiate medications as described above.

No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 26-minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy. EPISODES:
During the recording as photic stimulation was being performed the patient started stuttering and her right arm started shaking and trembling for a period of 11 minutes.  The patient is responsive throughout the whole period; however, the code word which she was asked to memorize and later asked to repeat was repeated incorrectly at the end of the event. IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.

The episode described above, which started on with the right arm shaking did not reveal any EEG correlate, as such it may represent a nonepileptic event or alternatively it may be a simple partial seizure, which in up to 75% of the cases do not have any EEG correlate.  Lastly, please note that the excessive beta noted on the EEG may be due to a medication effect.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 10-11 Hz in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is diffuse low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  A stage II was characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 70 beats per minutes and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage II sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, the repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturates, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 28-year-old woman with daily staring spells lasting less than a minute.  Also, right sided facial pain since she fell from a horse in 2010.  Normal MRI.

INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and generous beta.
The patient seems to be quite drowsy with hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  Rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness was noted with the characteristic 5 Hz flat top shape with rhythmic theta from the right temporal region.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  There was a fair amount of muscle artifact during photic stimulation.
Hyperventilation elicited paroxysmal, high amplitude slowing.  There is a small amount of shifting slowing noted in hyperventilation but the patient also appears to be quite drowsy, transitioning into sleep during hyperventilation.
Heart rate:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Rhythmic with temporal theta of drowsiness is a normal finding and is considered a normal variant.  There is a somewhat asynchronous hyperventilation response.  This is a nonspecific finding and is not necessarily pathological.  In this patient with episodes of staring, perhaps a more prolonged spell looking for additional drowsy bursts may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old right-handed female with a complaint of a syncopal event on March 25, 2013.  Apparently she fainted and was on the floor for 15 seconds and then was observed to shake.  Of note, during the recording here in the laboratory, there was a brief episode of right hemibody tingling.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The recording start time was 11:29 a.m.  The recording end time was 12 noon.  The recording length was 25 minutes.
As the record opens there is a well formed and symmetric 9-10 Hz  posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity that is symmetrically distributed.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm.  At approximately 11:45 a.m., approximately 15 minutes into the recording epic, the patient complained of right hemibody tingling and numbness.  She was examined by the physician in the laboratory at the time, and there were no obvious clinical sequela.  During this time, there was no change in the background cerebral activity of the EEG.
Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and induced a very reactive and responsive photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges.  The patient's heart rate ranged from 70-90 beats during the record epic.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does no rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  The brief clinical event of right hemibody numbness and tingling were not associated with changes in the background cerebral activity.  Thus, this event is likely a nonepileptic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 18-year-old, left handed male, with a history of head trauma at age 6 without loss of consciousness.  At the age of 10 to 11 he began to develop episodes of visual and auditory hallucinations.  These currently occur approximately every day and last between 10-15 minutes.
RECORDING TIMES:  Recording start time was 8:43 a.m. and recording end time was 9:06 a.m.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the record opens there is a well formed medium to high amplitude 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm that is briskly reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity identified which is symmetrically distributed.
During stage 1 sleep there is attenuation of the existing posterior dominant rhythm and the appearance of 5-6 Hz theta activity.  There is also a decrease in eye blinks and the appearance of slow rolling eye movements.  Stage 2 sleep is heralded by vertex waves and 14 Hz central sleep spindles.
Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing.
Photic stimulation is performed at intermediate and high flash frequency ranges and induces a symmetric photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges.
There were no spikes or sharp waves detected.  There were no electrographic seizures detected.  Of note, the clinically described episodes of visual or auditory hallucinations were not captured during this recording EPOC.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated long term monitoring, either inpatient or outpatient, may be indicated in this patient.

HISTORY:  A 62-year-old woman with past medical history of anxiety that has been having constant jerking episodes when falling asleep of her extremities, abdomen and face that lately have worsened in frequency and have become intolerable and do not permit her to go to sleep. DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
The patient is recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Overall, the background appears to be normal.  However, as the patient becomes drowsy, intermittent muscle artifact jerks can be seen throughout the recording, at times the EMG artifact could be noted more over the left temporalis muscle than the right.  There appears to be no preceding cortical discharge prior to this muscle artifact.  The video does not reveal clear facial jerks although the technician reports that she noticed some facial jerking irregularly. At one point, the patient does have some abdominal flexion which occurs congruously or at the same time as the muscle artifact occurred. Again, none of these artifacts have a preceding cortical discharge that could be clearly seen.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that the jerking episodes described above had no clear cortical or electrographic discharge and may be muscular discharges or possible myoclonus of subcortical origin.  No clear seizures were seen.

The patient seems to be very drowsy, she was falling asleep prior to hyperventilation and is falling asleep during hyperventilation.  Following hyperventilation rhythmic central theta was followed by vertex waves.  Spontaneous arousals were noted from stage 1 sleep.  A scant amount of artifact which may represent a snore was noted, but audible snoring was not identified on the video.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep and demonstrated harmonic and supra-harmonic driving.  The patient started to transition back into stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation.
Heart rate:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  This individual appeared to be quite sleepy as would be the case if this were a sleep deprived individual, an individual sleep deprived for this study or a person with an underlying sleep disturbance.  If additional information is needed a repeat study in the lab may be of value.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 42-year-old woman with a history of seizures.  Her last seizure occurred about 1 week ago while the patient was asleep.  The seizure was described as generalized tonic/clonic convulsion.  Of note, the patient was just diagnosed with colon cancer.

INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude of 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates.  Bursts of diffuse high amplitude centrally predominant theta are captured.  Also symmetrical vertex sleep spindles and K complexes are observed.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetric driving at multiple flash frequencies. Excess diffuse beta is captured.
FINDINGS:
Stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 22-minute EEG.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication affect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since the age of 8.  Most recent seizure June/July 2012 with fainting, falling, and shaking.  Now 4 months pregnant.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and asleep record.
TECHNICAL:  Impedances for most of the electrodes were satisfactory, but this EEG was problematic with a great degree of muscle artifact when the patient was awake.  As the patient went off to sleep, there was still muscle artifact picked up in the left scalp electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems described above, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of focal frontal central beta.  Wicket was noted as the patient became drowsy.  Other features with drowsiness include rhythmic central theta.  The electrode artifact did not drop out in stage I sleep with vertex waves.  Brief stage II sleep included vertex waves with spindles.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was remarkable for a great deal of muscle artifact.  Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The wicket is a normal finding.  Given the degree of muscle artifact described above, a follow-up study capturing perhaps more prolonged
sleep or with other mechanisms to alleviate the muscle artifact is suggested.  Alternatively, comparison with this individual's childhood EEGs may be of value.
